 ## Performance Considerations
 
-### N+1 and heavy traversal
-- Avoid per-file spawn loops to prevent O(N) process overhead.
-- Prefer one recursive `find` + one filtering pass + one validator call.
-- Use `grep -l` style probes to keep output minimal when checking manifest markers.
+### N+1 and Scan Patterns
+Avoid nested file-level validation calls that multiply command overhead. Prefer one manifest list and one validator call unless required per-tool behavior dictates otherwise. Prune `find` with `-path` exclusions at source to avoid scanning `node_modules` and `.git`.
 
-### Memory usage
-- Keep discovered file list as newline-separated string to avoid large arrays in memory.
-- Write validator logs directly to OUTDIR files, not buffered in shell variables.
+### Memory Usage
+Avoid building huge bash arrays with every path when possible; use newline-separated strings and per-step streaming to logs. This is adequate for large trees and keeps shell memory stable.
 
-### Caching opportunities
-- No durable cache is needed: validation is stateless and external validators already cache local schemas.
-- Optional future optimization: cache workspace file walk when multiple kube steps are added.
+### Caching and Reuse
+No cross-run cache is needed. Within a run, cache selected validator name and discovered manifest list to avoid recomputation between command paths.
 
-### Potential hot paths
-- Large monorepo with thousands of YAMLs: marker scan dominates. Document expected runtime and rely on `CHANGED_FILES` for pull-request scoped runs.
-- Large file sets plus `kubeconform -summary -output json` can be verbose; use `MAX_LINES` truncation and full log path.
+### Hot Paths
+Fast path is clean repos with no Kubernetes files: ensure low-cost discovery and immediate SKIP.
+Slow path is large monorepos with many YAML files: tune exclusion list and avoid repeated grep passes if possible.
 
